<font color="#FF0000">DIXIE, AND OTHERS COMING HOME</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jul  4  1:53:06 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
This is the first time I have visited the POV site, and the first time I have ever risked putting myself out there by writing.  Its hard sometimes for us to come out in the open.  As I have read the notes, especially from younger people wanting to know what happened, the tears come.  I have grief and sadness and a richer life today because I spent my youth in Viet Nam.  The guilt, the rage, and the spiritual, emotional, and physical pain are diminished.<br>
Dixie, Welcome Home!  &quot;Dazed and confused&quot; is the welcome home greeting.  I have many friends today who are Viet Nam vets.  We talk about it, mostly when we can be of help to someone like you.  In talking with vets, I know that it doesn't matter if you were in the boonies, on a ship, at an air base.  It doesn't matter what your contribution was.  For those of us who came back alive, there is guilt.  We didn't do enough if we are not dead.  My dad feels that way about not going over seas during WWII.<br>
I pretended I was OK for over 20 years.  Then I had to do the work, feel the pain, and open the door to the past.  I can't agree more with Edward Ramon...get in touch with the nearest Vet Center.  They are vets, and they are experts.  I ended up going to the Wall, sitting at the grave of a friend at Arlington, and talking to his family.  But the first step was asking for help, and visiting the Vet Center.<br>
Welcome home, sister.  You are one of us.  We embrase you.  You are not alone.
<p><code>-- RLJONES1@WORLDNET.ATT.NET  (Rich Jones) </code><p>


